  "output": "## Codebase context\n\nThis is a Python asyncio CLI (job-board scraper + SQLite dedup + notifiers), not a web app â€” there's no React frontend and no traditional multi-table ORM. I've mapped your five categories onto their closest Python equivalents. Core files reviewed in full: `store.py`, `pipeline.py`, `filters.py`, `models.py`, `fetchers.py`, `notify.py`, `agent.py` (1,505 lines total).\n\n---\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern â€” `store.py:60-72` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job, you issue a separate `SELECT`, then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`. With ~15 sources Ă— up to 40 paginated pages each, this can be thousands of individual round-trips per run.\n\n```python\n# current â€” one SELECT + one INSERT/UPDATE per job, in a Python loop\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nFix: one batched `SELECT ... WHERE key IN (...)` to build a lookup dict, then `executemany` for writes. Also compute `job.to_row()` once instead of twice (it currently gets recomputed inside `_insert`/`_update` after already comparing `job.content_hash`):\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 500):        # SQLite host-param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 500]\n        ph = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        cur.execute(f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({ph})\", chunk)\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in cur.fetchall()})\n\n    new, changed, unchanged = [], [], []\n    inserts, updates = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}     # content_hash computed once\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); inserts.append(row)\n        elif h != row[\"content_hash\"]:\n            changed.append(job); updates.append(row)\n        else:\n            unchanged.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if inserts:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id, title,\n            url, location, department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range,\n            content_hash, first_seen, last_seen)\n            VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,:location,\n            :department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,:content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\",\n            inserts)\n    if updates:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url, location=:location,\n            department=:department, employment_type=:employment_type, posted_at=:posted_at,\n            salary_range=:salary_range, content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now\n            WHERE key=:key\"\"\", updates)\n    if unchanged:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", unchanged)\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(3n) individual statements into O(1) batch statements (chunked only for the `IN` clause).\n\n---\n\n### 2. Unnecessary re-renders (React) â€” not applicable\n\nNo frontend framework exists in this repo (no `.jsx`/`.tsx`/`package.json`). Nothing to check here.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Redundant computations â€” `filters.py:11-27`\n\n`match()` recompiles the include/exclude regex patterns **from scratch for every single job**:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every call\n```\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, so with N jobs and M keyword patterns you get up to `2*N*M` `re.compile()` calls instead of `2*M`. Fix â€” compile once outside the loop:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = [l.lower() for l in (rules.get(\"locations\") or [])]\n\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\n\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] = (), exclude: list[re.Pattern] = (),\n          locations: list[str] = (), cutoff: datetime | None = None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    if locations:\n        loc = job.location.lower()\n        if not any(l in loc for l in locations):\n            return False\n    if cutoff is not None:\n        dt = job.posted_dt\n        if dt is not None and dt < cutoff:\n            return False\n    return True\n```\n\nSecondary spot: `Job.content_hash` (`models.py:66`) is an uncached `@property` â€” recomputes a SHA-256 hash on every access. It's already fixed as a side effect of the `store.py` change above (computed once via `to_row()`), but if it's accessed elsewhere in the future, since `Job` uses `@dataclass(slots=True)` you can't use `functools.cached_property` (needs `__dict__`) â€” you'd need a manual slot-based cache:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _content_hash: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False, init=False)\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._content_hash is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._content_hash = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode(\"utf-8\")).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._content_hash\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. Caching opportunities\n\n- **Cross-run HTTP caching is unused.** Every 12h scheduled run (`.github/workflows/scrape.yaml`) refetches the *entire* board from every source, even though most listings haven't changed. Your `store.py` already has a generic `meta` KV table (used for the scan marker) â€” reuse it to stash `ETag`/`Last-Modified` per source and send conditional headers:\n  ```python\n  etag = store.get_meta(f\"etag:{source['ats']}:{company}\")\n  headers = {\"If-None-Match\": etag} if etag else {}\n  r = await client.get(url, headers=headers)\n  if r.status_code == 304:\n      return []  # nothing changed, skip parsing entirely\n  store.set_meta(f\"etag:{source['ats']}:{company}\", r.headers.get(\"ETag\", \"\"))\n  ```\n  Not all ATS platforms send these headers, but it costs nothing to try, and for the ones that do (many do via CDN) you skip parsing + dedup work entirely.\n\n- **Sequential pagination could be parallelized once the total is known.** `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_workday` all get a `total`/`total count` back on the *first* page, then still fetch every subsequent page one-at-a-time (`max_pages` defaults up to 40). Example for `fetch_amazon`:\n  ```python\n  first = await _get_json(client, url, params={**base, \"offset\": 0}, headers=...)\n  jobs_raw = (first or {}).get(\"jobs\") or []\n  total = (first or {}).get(\"hits\", len(jobs_raw))\n  pages_needed = min(max_pages, -(-total // 10))\n  rest = await asyncio.gather(*(\n      _get_json(client, url, params={**base, \"offset\": pg * 10}, headers=...)\n      for pg in range(1, pages_needed)\n  ))\n  ```\n  This turns ~40 sequential round trips into 1 + up to 39 concurrent ones per source. Caveat: add a small per-source semaphore (e.g. 4) so this doesn't look like a burst attack and trigger 429s â€” your existing `_request` retry/backoff wrapper will absorb some of that, but it's safer to cap concurrency explicitly.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Memory leaks\n\nThis runs as a **short-lived GitHub Actions process every 12h** (confirmed via `6ae8083`), not a long-running daemon â€” so classic accumulate-forever leaks (growing caches, unclosed listeners across requests) don't apply here. I checked the two places that would matter if that ever changed:\n\n- `httpx.AsyncClient` in `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:770-787`) is correctly closed in a `finally` block, including on exceptions.\n- `Store` connections are always used via `with Store(...) as store:` (both `pipeline.py:42` and `agent.py:73/126`), so `sqlite3.Connection.close()` always runs.\n\nOne latent risk worth a one-line comment if this code is ever reused in a long-lived process: `parse_google` deliberately truncates `raw` to `{\"id\", \"brand\"}` to avoid holding full server-rendered blobs in memory (per its own comment), but every *other* parser (`parse_greenhouse`, `parse_lever`, `parse_ashby`, etc.) keeps the entire raw JSON payload per job in `Job.raw` for the whole run even though only `to_row()` (which drops `raw`) ever gets persisted. Fine for a one-shot process; would become a real leak if this pipeline were ever adapted into a persistent worker that holds `Job` objects across cycles.\n\n---\n\n### Priority order\n1. **`store.py` batched diff** â€” highest impact, zero behavior change, straightforward.\n2. **`filters.py` regex hoist** â€” trivial fix, scales with job-list size.\n3. **ETag caching via existing `meta` table** â€” good ROI given the 12h cron cadence.\n4. **Parallel pagination** â€” biggest wall-clock win but needs a concurrency cap to be safe against rate limits.\n",
